crops.description: A small slender-stemmed palm, about 15 feet high, with pinnate leaves. For previous introduction see 104681.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: A small shrub with drooping branches and rounded leaves, the two lobes rounded oval, white-hairy beneath. The small yellow flowers are in racemes of 12 to 18.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: A palm, with a short thick trunk up to 6 feet high and 1 foot thick, having a crown of reniform palmately divided leaves 4 to 6 feet across on petioles about 5 feet long, which are armed below the middle with recurved brown spines more than an inch long. For previous introduction see 93412.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: A slender palm about 50 feet high, with a crown of large fan-shaped leaves. For previous introduction see 104240.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: For previous introduction and description see 105448.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: A large tropical tree, 40 to 60 feet high, with compound leaves a foot or less in length, the two to four broadly elliptic leaves being 2 to 4 inches long. The white flowers are in small corymbs.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: Plants of a tropical tree of moderate size, with ovate or rounded thick leaves 5 or 6 inches long and fragrant white flowers. 2 inches long, in corymblike clusters.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos
crops.description: An evergreen tree with alternate pinnate leaves and racemes of purplish pea-like flowers. For previous introduction see 94776.

crops.origin: Central Mercedita, Pinar del Rio, Cuba
crops.presented_by: W. A. Mace, Madruga, Cuba, and L. H. Dewey, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: A tree, native to the East Indies, 30 to 40 feet high, with viscid milky juice and leathery ovate leaves 3 feet long, entire at the base but divided above into 3 to 9 lobes. The large fruits, 4 to 6 inches in diameter, are often seedless, but in this variety the seeds are present and are much the size, shape, and flavor of chestnuts. For previous introduction see 80173.

crops.presented_by: Julius Matz, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: Variety Zorzalena. A relatively tender variety. The tree is leafy, compact, and a good early bearer whose fruit is grown for its oil.

The soft coarse pithlike wood is white or yellowish and is used for making canoes and rafts. For previous introduction see 98928.
